WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.600
My talk today is going to be about Project Immortality.

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:10.720
It's about using GitHub to make your work live forever.

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:14.000
You can follow me on Twitter, at underscore Tan Ho.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.280
Slides are, this is actually a GitHub repository, but the slides are uploaded to that.

00:00:18.280 --> 00:00:19.280
Okay.

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:40.400
So, I'd like to start by, wait a second, clicker, yes, we like clickers, okay.

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:44.880
So I'd like to introduce you to the life and times of a data science project, okay?

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:47.840
This might sound familiar to most of you, certainly the story of most of my projects

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:49.400
if not all of them.

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:55.560
You start by importing some data, okay, whether that's from scraping, APIs, a database, pre-existing

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:58.160
data, stuff that your company has, whatever it is, okay?

00:00:58.160 --> 00:00:59.720
You start by importing some data.

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:00.720
Then you get to know this data.

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:03.400
You do some wrangling, you do some feature engineering, you start doing some exploratory

00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:07.559
data analysis, trying to understand how messy the data is and how bad your data is, shout

00:01:07.559 --> 00:01:09.239
out to Jim.

00:01:09.239 --> 00:01:12.480
And then once you've kind of done with that, you kind of understand that data a little

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:15.720
bit as from a human perspective, you start trying to teach your computer to do something

00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:16.720
with it.

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:22.040
You try to model, you try to get some clustering done or regressions or try to predict a number.

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:27.400
And then you study the results of that output, you plot it, and then you tweet the plot,

00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:28.400
okay?

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:32.040
So, you know, you share it with the world, you've learned something, here's what I've

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:36.800
learned, here's, you know, get some feedback on it, validation, 15 minutes of fame, hopefully.

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:42.879
Hopefully everyone likes it, you get some feedback, and then most projects die here,

00:01:42.879 --> 00:01:43.879
right?

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:48.199
And it's rightfully so, because you've learned something, you've done what you set out to

00:01:48.199 --> 00:01:52.000
do, you've learned something from that project and you're ready to move on.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.800
Sometime later, this happens.

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:57.400
Relevant XKCD as ever?

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:03.000
Never have I ever felt so close to another soul and yet so helplessly alone as when I

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.680
Googled this problem and there's one result, a thread by someone who studied the exact

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:12.919
same problem that I'm interested in and was last posted to in 2020, 2020 feels like 2003,

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:15.279
Who were you, Denver Coder 9?

00:02:15.279 --> 00:02:16.440
Who were you, Tan?

00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:17.440
What did you see?

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:19.839
What did you learn?

00:02:19.839 --> 00:02:21.600
This story happens a lot, right?

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:25.119
And whether it's a Stack Overflow answer, a problem, a GitHub, sometimes now you'll

00:02:25.119 --> 00:02:27.279
Google and you'll find a Twitter thread.

00:02:27.279 --> 00:02:28.279
How do you help this person?

00:02:28.279 --> 00:02:31.199
Actually, I'm not that interested in how you help that person, because the answer is they'll

00:02:31.199 --> 00:02:35.839
reach out to you, if you're available, you'll spend time and energy and you'll give it back

00:02:35.839 --> 00:02:37.600
to them if you have time, right?

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:41.800
What I'm actually more interested in is how can your project help this person?

00:02:41.800 --> 00:02:43.679
Because at the end of the day, that's not always possible.

00:02:43.679 --> 00:02:49.240
Whether you're constrained, your time has limits, your energy has limits, your project

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:53.000
should be able to help them and get what they need from it and move on.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.279
So my question, my talk today is going to be about how can you help your project help

00:02:57.279 --> 00:02:58.279
this person?

00:02:58.279 --> 00:03:03.919
And I think that there's, oh, skipped a slide on me, that GitHub has a bunch of resources

00:03:03.919 --> 00:03:08.520
that can really help you along this path.

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:10.639
So who this talk is for?

00:03:10.639 --> 00:03:13.839
This talk is for people who are doing personal hobby projects, it's for people who are doing

00:03:13.839 --> 00:03:18.000
academic research, it's for people who are interested in public and open source work.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.559
More broadly, it's for people who don't have a budget when they're doing their work and

00:03:22.559 --> 00:03:27.199
the people who are interested in helping others use their work and helping their projects

00:03:27.199 --> 00:03:28.199
live on.

00:03:28.199 --> 00:03:30.479
So why do I care so much about this?

00:03:30.479 --> 00:03:31.479
This is me.

00:03:31.479 --> 00:03:35.559
This is literally my profile picture on every single Twitter and Twitch and everything else

00:03:35.559 --> 00:03:36.559
about me.

00:03:37.559 --> 00:03:41.320
In a past life, I was a property manager, grew up in the family business, absolutely

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:43.360
hated that job, okay?

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:50.440
So on the side, I started doing fantasy football, started analyzing it, started teaching myself

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:54.399
some data analysis to go with it, started with Excel, Power Query, eventually learned

00:03:54.399 --> 00:03:59.199
R, taught myself basically football analysis, NFL, fantasy football, et cetera.

00:03:59.199 --> 00:04:02.600
Eventually that led to a data science career.

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:08.160
I got a job in a home building company doing data science and doing programming, and recently

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:11.080
I've just accepted a position with Zealous Analytics to work on pro soccer.

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:18.320
So you can make that career switch if you're interested by doing this sort of thing.

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:23.320
And then today, along the way, I've become a maintainer of public NFL data, and I maintain

00:04:23.320 --> 00:04:27.760
NFL-verse and FF-verse art packages for NFL and fantasy football, respectively.

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:29.000
So why do I care so much about this?

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:30.799
I've been the hobbyist programmer.

00:04:30.799 --> 00:04:35.119
I've been the person who's broke and wanting to do stuff without a budget.

00:04:35.119 --> 00:04:39.640
And I care today, even still, about making sure that people can build on my work and

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:43.839
can use my work in their own projects.

00:04:43.839 --> 00:04:46.200
So let's talk about one of my projects, FF Opportunity.

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:49.959
So it's a project that uses NFL play-by-play data to study expected fantasy points.

00:04:49.959 --> 00:04:54.079
Now, I'm not going to go into the details about NFL or expected fantasy points, you

00:04:54.079 --> 00:04:57.720
don't need to know anything about that, but if you're interested, expected fantasy points

00:04:57.720 --> 00:05:00.200
help measure the value of play opportunities in fantasy football.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:04.640
And you can find my project here, github.com, FF-verse, FF Opportunity.

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:06.239
I'll take you through the structure anyway, though.

00:05:06.239 --> 00:05:08.920
So this might sound familiar.

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:14.600
You start by importing some NFL-verse play-by-play data, then I wrangled some features together,

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:21.200
trained an XGBoost model, and then used that model to predict fantasy points, right?

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:24.480
This is the story of every machine learning project, every data science project, really.

00:05:24.480 --> 00:05:25.959
Now what?

00:05:25.959 --> 00:05:29.160
How can I make FF Opportunity live on?

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:33.320
I'm actually going to frame this question, what is this person who stumbles on my project

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:37.679
later interested in, and what kind of questions are they going to be asking?

00:05:37.679 --> 00:05:39.720
How can they use and improve on my model?

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.480
No model is perfect, but they're useful.

00:05:42.480 --> 00:05:47.399
And then understanding how past work has, understanding the past work in that field

00:05:47.399 --> 00:05:52.079
can help you improve on that model, where the gaps are, understand how to use it, understand

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:56.440
how to improve it, where the, you know, that kind of thing.

00:05:56.440 --> 00:05:58.160
Can new predictions be automated every week?

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:01.640
Maybe they're good with this model, but they're interested in how the prediction, what the

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:05.040
predictions are and what the model says about games that haven't happened yet and games

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:06.640
that are going to happen soon.

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:10.119
So can you automate new predictions every week of the NFL season?

00:06:10.119 --> 00:06:16.880
There's a new slate of games every week from September through to January, February.

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:18.839
Lastly, where can they find these predictions?

00:06:18.839 --> 00:06:23.119
Where can I put it, where can they access the predictions in a way that's not trying

00:06:23.119 --> 00:06:27.399
to, you know, ask me to email them or tweet them or send them these predictions?

00:06:27.399 --> 00:06:29.040
It's no good if it lives in my computer, right?

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:31.000
So let's go through these questions one by one.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:33.040
Can someone use and improve on my model?

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:37.440
There's a lot of work in the R space now in terms of reproducibility.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:40.480
RNV is a great option, Docker is a great option.

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:43.720
The one I actually like to use is making it a package, and I'm not talking about making

00:06:43.720 --> 00:06:48.279
it for CRAN, but I think there's two elements of packages that I think are really underrated

00:06:48.279 --> 00:06:50.920
and help kind of build things going forward.

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:55.320
One of them is adding a description file, and the other one is wrapping code into functions.

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:59.959
Adding a description file, one of the things that adding a description file does, it forces

00:06:59.959 --> 00:07:01.880
you or asks you to add a license.

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:06.920
And a license is really important, especially when you're doing public work, because it

00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:10.119
tells people what you're okay with them doing with your work, right?

00:07:10.119 --> 00:07:13.760
So if you want them to, if you're okay with them doing anything with that, say so.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:17.279
Add an MIT license, that's what that's basically there for.

00:07:17.279 --> 00:07:21.279
If you want them to only use this work to help extend public work, you can use a license

00:07:21.279 --> 00:07:22.959
like GPLv3, right?

00:07:22.959 --> 00:07:27.480
So just choosing the license helps communicate that you want them to use that work.

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:31.839
And by sharing that work to them with that license, people can understand what you're

00:07:31.839 --> 00:07:34.040
okay with them doing with it.

00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:38.200
The other thing that it does is it makes dependencies, it makes installation of dependencies really

00:07:38.200 --> 00:07:42.679
easy, because you're forced to list all the dependencies, and if you're able to also list

00:07:42.679 --> 00:07:48.480
the minimum versions, it makes things like remotes or Pac or Pac-Man work, because they

00:07:48.480 --> 00:07:52.799
can read the description file from GitHub and then install all the dependencies for

00:07:52.799 --> 00:07:56.760
you while you're installing this package, or this package.

00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:59.399
And even if it doesn't have any functions in it, it'll still install the dependencies

00:07:59.399 --> 00:08:03.720
for you, and then you can use that in, you know, running the script after you've cloned

00:08:03.720 --> 00:08:04.720
it on GitHub.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:08.200
Of course, Useless has this covered, so you don't actually need to type out a description

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:09.200
file.

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:12.480
It's got four functions that you need to know to do exactly what I'm talking about.

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:16.480
Use description, use MIT license, use package for each package that you're using, and once

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:20.799
you've added all the packages, you use latest dependencies, and it's gonna version lock

00:08:20.799 --> 00:08:22.160
the version that's on your machine.

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:30.399
So it'll put that in as the minimum version, and then, you know, you set this up for success.

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:33.520
The other thing that I like to do, this is kind of the next level, is to wrap logic into

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:35.799
functions.

00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:37.400
It's really easy for users.

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:40.760
So from your end of things, what you need to do is convert the hard-coded variables

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:42.880
and data frames to arguments.

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:49.559
Extract function is a cool feature in RStudio, Ctrl-Alt-X, and then if you copy and paste

00:08:49.559 --> 00:08:54.760
or if you select the entire code chunk, and you press this shortcut, I think it's Command-Option-X.

00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:57.919
I don't use a Mac, but it's related.

00:08:57.919 --> 00:09:02.559
It'll automagically create a function and put the skeleton of your code in a function

00:09:02.559 --> 00:09:05.119
and take all the variables and put them into arguments.

00:09:05.119 --> 00:09:08.679
So this already basically does it for you, and then the other thing you can do is add

00:09:08.679 --> 00:09:09.679
some usage notes.

00:09:09.679 --> 00:09:13.359
And I say documentation here because documentation scares people, but really understanding how

00:09:13.359 --> 00:09:18.280
you use logic, how you use the function, and what the function's meant to do will help

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:20.559
other people kind of understand where you're going with it.

00:09:20.559 --> 00:09:24.080
And the goal is to make it easy for users to run, right?

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:26.119
So our users love functions.

00:09:26.119 --> 00:09:28.880
They understand exactly what to do when you give them a function, you put arguments into

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:31.880
it, and then you kind of go from there.

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:32.880
Okay.

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:33.880
So we talked about packages.

00:09:33.880 --> 00:09:34.880
That's the bare minimum.

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:35.880
There's a whole bunch more on packages.

00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:39.119
There's a whole book on it.

00:09:39.119 --> 00:09:41.919
But from my end of things, that's the bare minimum.

00:09:41.919 --> 00:09:45.239
The next thing I'm going to talk about is how can you predict new...

00:09:45.239 --> 00:09:48.280
Can you automate predictions every week, right?

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:52.799
Because the users who don't care about the model itself are really only interested in

00:09:52.799 --> 00:09:53.799
the output of the model.

00:09:53.799 --> 00:09:57.119
So can you automate giving them a model every single week?

00:09:57.119 --> 00:10:00.640
The answer is yes, of course, with GitHub Actions.

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:08.719
This is literally the 20-line file that automates the FF opportunity predictions.

00:10:08.719 --> 00:10:13.119
And it uses the description file that we just talked about to run every night after

00:10:13.119 --> 00:10:14.119
every game.

00:10:14.119 --> 00:10:19.400
So that's 4 or 5 a.m. on Monday, Tuesday, and Friday, from September to January.

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:24.400
And then it installs R on the machine, the virtual machine, installs the packages from

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:27.760
the dependencies that I listed in my description, and then it runs a script.

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:28.760
And that's it.

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:30.260
That's all you need to do.

00:10:30.260 --> 00:10:33.520
So obviously there's a whole bunch of magic that happens in the back end here.

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:38.000
But from an end user perspective, as someone automating your projects, this is already...

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:43.239
You're leaning on a bunch of work by the RLib Actions team that is out there, and it's

00:10:43.239 --> 00:10:44.599
ready for you to use, right?

00:10:44.599 --> 00:10:45.960
And GitHub Actions is free.

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:50.640
If you've got public work, public projects, there's no action limits.

00:10:50.640 --> 00:10:51.640
Action minutes limits.

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:52.640
That sounded weird.

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:53.640
Anyways.

00:10:53.640 --> 00:10:59.159
The last question, and the one I think that more people need to know about, is where can

00:10:59.159 --> 00:11:01.320
I make predictions accessible?

00:11:01.320 --> 00:11:02.320
So if you're...

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:03.559
We're already talking about GitHub.

00:11:03.559 --> 00:11:08.280
So the common approach is to just commit things to your GitHub repository, right?

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:11.760
Well, there's three common problems with that.

00:11:11.760 --> 00:11:13.119
I'll talk about them here.

00:11:13.119 --> 00:11:16.039
File size limits, inefficient binary data storage, and commit history chaos.

00:11:16.039 --> 00:11:18.520
We'll start with file size limits.

00:11:18.520 --> 00:11:22.640
This is approximate, but I think the GitHub file size limits are something like 75 megabytes

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:24.919
per file and 2 gigabytes per repo.

00:11:24.919 --> 00:11:28.159
In today's modern age, that's basically nothing, right?

00:11:28.159 --> 00:11:30.119
So it's very easy to go through this.

00:11:30.119 --> 00:11:34.960
So if you have a CSV, for example, you might think, okay, well, maybe what I should do

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:41.119
is use an RDS file or a Parquet file to use Arrow or whatever kind of small file size.

00:11:41.119 --> 00:11:45.239
I think my friend Seb, he likes to use QS.

00:11:45.239 --> 00:11:46.239
Same idea.

00:11:46.239 --> 00:11:48.200
They're all binary files.

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:54.239
So the problem with that is that version control is incredibly bad at dealing with binary files.

00:11:54.239 --> 00:11:59.280
Here's an example of a repository that has a daily automation that basically overwrites

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:01.320
an RDS file every single day.

00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:03.679
It's really tiny, so I've annotated it for you.

00:12:03.679 --> 00:12:07.919
The actual data in this repository is 60 megabytes in size.

00:12:07.919 --> 00:12:13.840
And then Git, since this is over the course of six months or a year, has automatically

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:19.359
backed up 6 gigabytes worth of data that I didn't know about until I decided that I need

00:12:19.359 --> 00:12:22.320
to clone it down and do something with the code.

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:27.520
So then once I cloned it down, you can't push it back to GitHub because Git has a limit

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:29.640
of 2 gigabytes.

00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:35.359
So I actually, like, rage tweeted a whole bunch of this stuff when I found this out.

00:12:35.359 --> 00:12:38.500
If you're really keen, you can go find it.

00:12:38.500 --> 00:12:40.080
So it's incredibly bad.

00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:45.119
What's happening is that version control is literally tracking versions, right?

00:12:45.119 --> 00:12:48.419
And what it does, it compares the differences and tries to log the differences.

00:12:48.419 --> 00:12:53.479
But binary files are entirely different every time you write it.

00:12:53.479 --> 00:12:56.599
So Git naturally stores a copy, right?

00:12:56.679 --> 00:12:59.200
And that's why Git is really bad at dealing with binary files.

00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:04.200
So even if you're into parquet and the latest and greatest there, it's very quick, especially

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:07.840
when you pair it with actions, that you kill your repo like this.

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:10.239
Lastly, this is another problem.

00:13:10.239 --> 00:13:13.599
If you're committing to the same repo that your code lives in, you end up with, like,

00:13:13.599 --> 00:13:14.599
6,000 commits.

00:13:14.599 --> 00:13:16.280
Now, pop quiz.

00:13:16.280 --> 00:13:20.159
Which commit did I make a typo in and automatically write to the wrong file?

00:13:20.159 --> 00:13:22.520
Well, it was, like, 4,222 commits ago.

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:23.520
How do I revert to that?

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:24.520
Right?

00:13:24.520 --> 00:13:25.520
It's impossible.

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:29.000
So commit history chaos.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:30.919
There's obviously better solutions.

00:13:30.919 --> 00:13:33.599
Here's some meh solutions.

00:13:33.599 --> 00:13:34.760
There's Git large file storage.

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:37.359
It takes care of some of the large file size problems.

00:13:37.359 --> 00:13:39.840
But it also wrecks your Git repository.

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:41.919
It's impossible to collaborate with.

00:13:41.919 --> 00:13:45.840
It's really hard for users to work with because your data isn't actually stored on GitHub

00:13:45.840 --> 00:13:46.840
and files anymore.

00:13:46.840 --> 00:13:47.840
It's sharded everywhere.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:48.840
Amazon S3 buckets.

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:49.840
Two problems.

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:50.840
One, they cost money.

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:54.760
Again, we're talking about free, especially in sustainable projects.

00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:59.200
And the other problem is that it's stored away from your repository.

00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:03.280
So you have no idea what data is available for that repository.

00:14:03.280 --> 00:14:05.679
And so someone's got this bucket and it's got things on it.

00:14:05.679 --> 00:14:10.359
It's really hard to work with visually for the novice user, someone who's not accessing

00:14:10.359 --> 00:14:14.719
a terminal in a programming perspective to understand what data is there.

00:14:14.719 --> 00:14:18.039
Lastly, people still use Dropbox for this sort of problem.

00:14:18.039 --> 00:14:20.200
But that also really difficult to work with.

00:14:20.200 --> 00:14:21.880
But now from the command line side.

00:14:21.880 --> 00:14:24.559
How do you get files back and forth from there?

00:14:24.559 --> 00:14:29.719
The real solution, again, pairing with the GitHub theme, GitHub releases.

00:14:29.719 --> 00:14:33.359
And GitHub releases, it's kind of a lesser known thing.

00:14:33.359 --> 00:14:34.359
But you can make a new release.

00:14:34.359 --> 00:14:36.479
And releases are stored right next to your repo.

00:14:36.479 --> 00:14:40.559
So if you kind of go through this section beside your repo, there's releases.

00:14:40.559 --> 00:14:42.159
You make a new release.

00:14:42.159 --> 00:14:43.159
You upload files to the release.

00:14:43.159 --> 00:14:46.760
And then when you're ready, you can update those files as desired.

00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:49.880
How is this different from the other GitHub data repos?

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:51.700
Well, there's friendly file size limits.

00:14:51.700 --> 00:14:55.299
So each file that you upload to a release is understood to be bigger.

00:14:55.299 --> 00:14:58.659
So the actual limit for a file is, like, 2 gigabytes.

00:14:58.659 --> 00:15:01.500
And you can upload as many of these files as you want.

00:15:01.500 --> 00:15:06.219
So that's much more generous than 2 gigabytes in total and 75 megabytes.

00:15:06.219 --> 00:15:07.219
You version by choice.

00:15:07.219 --> 00:15:11.179
So when you upload, you overwrite the file unless you make a new release, right?

00:15:11.179 --> 00:15:14.419
And if you're ready to archive that data, you make a new release, upload to that new

00:15:14.419 --> 00:15:17.219
repository, and you still have the old version.

00:15:17.219 --> 00:15:18.659
You just commit history clean.

00:15:18.659 --> 00:15:19.659
You're manually uploading.

00:15:19.659 --> 00:15:21.419
You're uploading through an API.

00:15:21.419 --> 00:15:22.419
History stays with your project.

00:15:22.419 --> 00:15:26.500
So if I'm interested in what data is available within the NL first data package, you go through

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:27.500
the releases.

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:28.500
You figure it out.

00:15:28.500 --> 00:15:29.979
You can point and click and download.

00:15:29.979 --> 00:15:32.260
And best of all, it's free.

00:15:32.260 --> 00:15:35.340
Both for public and private repositories.

00:15:35.340 --> 00:15:37.419
Of course, R is wonderful.

00:15:37.419 --> 00:15:39.340
And there's a package for everything.

00:15:39.340 --> 00:15:47.419
The piggyback package, which I started working with, and it's originally by Carl Buttiger,

00:15:47.419 --> 00:15:50.219
came up with three functions that basically run that whole process.

00:15:50.219 --> 00:15:54.059
First is pb release create.

00:15:54.059 --> 00:15:55.059
You create a new release.

00:15:55.059 --> 00:15:57.859
Pb upload to upload a file to a specific release.

00:15:57.859 --> 00:16:02.619
Pb download lets you download all the files, some of the files, or just one file from that

00:16:02.619 --> 00:16:03.619
release.

00:16:03.619 --> 00:16:08.979
So, to recap, today I presented three tools for project immortality, talked about R package

00:16:08.979 --> 00:16:11.979
infrastructure to help make things easy to install and also to communicate what you want

00:16:11.979 --> 00:16:16.299
people to do with your work, talked about GitHub actions to schedule and automate things,

00:16:16.299 --> 00:16:20.780
and then GitHub releases as an awesome and wonderful way to store data.

00:16:20.780 --> 00:16:24.400
So with that, with those three tools under your belt, I'd like to leave you with one

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:26.099
last question.

00:16:26.099 --> 00:16:31.940
How can you help your projects help others now and into the future?

00:16:31.940 --> 00:16:32.940
Thank you.

